''The sea is ours'': landlocked Bolivia hopes a court will reopen path to the Pacific
The sailors patrol a naval headquarters lined with hardware in La Paz.
Public buildings display an ocean blue flag.
The naval bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon River are decorated with the motto: "The sea is ours by right.
Recovering it is a duty.”
Throughout landlocked Bolivia, the memory of the lost coastline and now in the hands of Chile after a bloody 19th-century conflict over resources is still alive, as is the desire to once again cross the Pacific Ocean.
These hopes may have reached the highest level in decades, as Bolivia awaits the decision of the International Court of Justice on October 1 after five years of deliberations.
“Bolivia has momentum, a spirit of unity and serenity and obviously is waiting for the result with a positive attitude,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will watch the ruling of the International Court of Justice on big screens throughout the country, in the hope that the Hague court will welcome Bolivia’s claim that – after decades of intermittent dialogue – Chile is obliged to negotiate, guaranteeing Bolivia an outlet on the sea of State competence.
Evo Morales, Bolivia's charismatic indigenous president - who is facing a controversial battle for reelection next year - has a lot at stake with Monday's ruling.
“We are very close to our return to the Pacific Ocean,” he promised at the end of August.
But some analysts believe that the court will hardly decide in favor of Bolivia and that little would change if it did.
The UN body based in the Netherlands has no power to assign Chilean territory and has specified that it will not determine the outcome of possible negotiations.
The fact that the International Court of Justice’s ruling comes just six months after the final pleadings indicates that the case “was not complicated,” said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
And far from advancing the Bolivian cause, the past four years may have delayed it.
"The problem of access to the sea has been monopolized by the current Bolivian administration," Zárate said.
Morale’s belligerent rhetoric has shattered any remaining good intentions of Chile, he suggested.
Bolivia and Chile will continue negotiations at some point, but it will be very difficult to continue the discussions following what happened.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia's representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court's decision-making process was particularly expeditious.
On Monday, Bolivia will be able to "enjoy extraordinary opportunity in relations with Chile" and will have the opportunity to "end 139 years of disagreements with mutual benefit," he explained.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales - one of Latin America's most popular presidents - was using the maritime issue as a political scam.
