John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Scottish Independent Schools maintain a curriculum of academic excellence and this continued in 2018 with another set of outstanding exam results, reinforced by individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other collective endeavors.
With over 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), aspire to provide the best level of service to their students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare students for further higher education, for their chosen careers and for their place in the world as global citizens.
As an education sector able to develop and adopt a personalized school curriculum, we note that modern languages continue to be a popular and in-demand subject within schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, the message will reach his brain.
If you speak to him in his mother tongue, the message will reach the heart.”
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely on English alone if we want to build relationships of trust with people from other countries.
From this year’s exam results, we can see that languages are at the top of the rankings, with the highest success rates within independent schools.
68% of pupils who studied foreign languages obtained the highest grades.
The data, collected from the 74 SCIS member schools, showed that 72% of students obtained the highest praise rating in Chinese, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish obtained the highest rating.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland are promoting foreign languages as key skills for children and young people, who will undoubtedly need them in the future.
Currently, languages, as a choice of subject, are considered at the same level as STEM subjects (science, technology, technique and mathematics) in the curricula of independent institutes and elsewhere.
A survey conducted by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014 found that the reasons employees indicated for the difficulty in covering jobs are attributable in 17% of cases to a lack of language skills.
This is why language skills are becoming increasingly essential to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more and more job opportunities requiring language proficiency, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of your chosen career, if you have learned a second language, you will have an effective advantage in the future with a lifelong skill like this.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically put a multilingual person ahead of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of over 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% were unable to speak a foreign language at a level sufficient to maintain a conversation and French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, 15%.
That is why investing in language teaching is so important for children today.
Knowledge of several languages, particularly those of developing economies, will give children a better chance of finding a viable job.
In Scotland, each school will differ in the languages taught.
Several schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered the most important for the UK looking to 2020, such as Mandarin Chinese or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be several languages to choose from in independent schools, with teacher staff specializing in that area.
Scottish Independent Schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills necessary for success, whatever their future may be.
There is no denying right now, in a global trading system, that languages continue to be fundamental to the future of the country, and this must be reflected in teaching.
In fact, modern languages should be considered "international communication skills."
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
We have to do it right.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
