North Korea Absolutely Refuses Unilateral Disarmament Without Confidence
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that maintaining sanctions was exacerbating the country's distrust of the United States, which in such circumstances would absolutely refuse to unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho said at the world body's General Assembly that North Korea has taken "important goodwill measures" over the past year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test site and committing to the non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
“But we don’t see any consistent response from the US,” he said.
“Without trust in the United States, there will be no security in our national security, and in such circumstances we absolutely refuse to disarm unilaterally first.”
Although Mr Ri reused the well-known complaints about Washington's resistance to a "phased" denuclearisation with which North Korea would be rewarded on the basis of gradual action, his statement was important because he did not entirely reject unilateral denuclearisation as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump during the first ever meeting between an incumbent US president and a North Korean leader, held in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work towards the “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula,” while Trump promised guarantees to North Korean security.
North Korea has sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must give up its nuclear weapons first.
Washington has also opposed calls to ease tough international sanctions on North Korea.
“The US insists on the need to ‘have denuclearisation first’ and to increase the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve their purpose in a coercive manner and even opposes the ‘declaration of an end to the war’,” Ri said.
“The idea that sanctions can bring us to our knees is an illusion of those who know nothing about us.
But the problem is that continuing sanctions is increasing our distrust.”
Ri made no reference to plans for a second meeting between Kim and Trump that the U.S. leader had announced at the U.N. earlier this week.
The minister stressed the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months and added: “If the counterpart to this issue of denuclearization were South Korea and not the US, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be at this standstill.”
But even so, the tone of Ri’s speech was significantly different from last year’s speech at the UN General Assembly, when he said it was inevitable to target US territory with North Korea’s missiles after “the evil president” Trump had called Kim a “missile man” engaged in a suicide mission.
Before the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to “completely destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in taking the path of disarmament, but said much more needs to be done and that sanctions will remain in place until North Korea’s denuclearization.
On Wednesday, Trump said he did not have a deadline, stating that “whether it’s going to take two years, three years or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia say the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday: “Compliance with the Security Council sanctions must continue with force and without exception until complete, final and ascertained denuclearization is achieved.”
The Security Council unanimously backed sanctions controlling North Korea in 2006 in an attempt to stifle funding for nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and later said he would visit Pyongyang again the following month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea already three times this year, but the last trip did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July saying progress had been made, but a few hours later North Korea accused him of having filed “gangster requests.”
North Korea pledged during a meeting this month with Moon to dismantle a missile site and a nuclear complex if the U.S. took “compliant measures.”
He said Kim had explained to him that the “compliant measures” he wanted were security guarantees to which Trump had committed himself in Singapore and actions towards a normalization of relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on how to get enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has pushed all its students to sleep more in an attempt to counter the growing manly culture of studying for whole nights powered by caffeine.
One university scholar has found that students at the world’s number one university often have no idea of the basic concepts of caring for oneself.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, developed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the US.
He had the idea to start the course after a lecture he had given on the impact of lack of sleep on learning.
“At last a girl came to me and said, ‘Why am I only being told this now, when I’m in my senior year?’
She said no one had ever told her anything about the importance of sleep, which surprised me a lot,” she told The Telegraph.
The course, taught for the first time this year, explains to students the essential concepts of how good sleep-related habits can help academic and athletic performance as well as improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and director general of the university’s health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students suffered from a severe lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive activities.
In a section there is the image of a dorm room, where students can select coffee mugs, curtains, sneakers and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by lack of sleep, and the importance of an evening routine.
In another section, participants are explained how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
A campus map, with interactive icons, then encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that it will not immediately change the behavior of students.
But we believe that they have a right to know, just as you have a right to know the health effects of choosing to smoke cigarettes,” added Prof. Czeisler.
The culture of pride tied to the “white night to study” still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students lead to lack of sleep being a growing problem.
Sleeping enough and with a good quality sleep should be the students' secret weapon to combat stress, fatigue, anxiety, explained and even should serve to avoid gaining weight since lack of sleep brings the brain into starvation mode, making people constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student enrolled in the faculty of chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler develop the course, after taking one of his lectures last year during his first year at Harvard.
He explained that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to promote a campus-wide course.
The next step, he hopes, will be to ask all graduate students to follow a similar program of study before enrolling at this competitive institute.
Professor Czeisler advised students to set an alarm clock for when they need to go to bed, as well as when they need to wake up, and to be aware of the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can tilt the circadian rhythm, leading to sleep problems.
