New Cancer Vaccine May Teach Immune System to ‘See’ Malignant Cells
New Cancer Vaccine May Teach the Immune System to “See” Malignant Cells and Kill Them
The vaccine teaches the immune system to recognize malignant cells as part of treatment
The method involves the extraction of immune cells from a patient, and their alteration in the laboratory
They can then "see" a protein common to numerous types of cancer and are then reinjected
An experimental trial of this vaccine is giving promising results in patients with different types of cancer.
A woman treated with the vaccine that teaches the immune system to recognize malignant cells has seen her ovarian cancer disappear for more than 18 months.
The method involves extracting immune cells from a patient and altering them in the lab so that they can “see” a protein common to numerous cancers, called HER2, and then those cells are re-injected.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the U.S. National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, said: “Our findings indicate that we have a very promising vaccine.”
The HER2 protein “promotes the growth of different types of cancer,” including breast, ovarian, lung and colorectal cancer, Prof. Berzofsky explained.
A similar procedure of extracting immune cells from patients to “teach” them how to target cancer cells worked in the treatment of a type of leukemia.
