What is the Global Citizen Festival and has it done something to reduce poverty?
This Saturday New York will host the Global Citizen Festival, an annual music event that sees the performance of a remarkable run of stars and has an equally remarkable mission: to end poverty in the world.
In its seventh edition, the Global Citizen Festival will see tens of thousands of people pour onto Central Park’s Great Lawn not only to enjoy performances like those of Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes, but also to raise awareness about the event’s real purpose, which is to end extreme poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival, which began in 2012, is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, an international support group that hopes to eradicate poverty by increasing the number of people actively fighting it.
In order to receive a free ticket to the event (unless you were willing to pay for a VIP ticket), the concert audience had to complete a series of tasks, or “actions” such as volunteering, emailing a world leader, making a phone call, or any other significant way that would help raise awareness about their goal of eradicating poverty.
But, precisely, how successful has the Global Citizen Festival been now that 12 years remain to achieve its intended purpose?
Is the idea of rewarding people with a free concert really a genuine way to persuade people to call for action, or is it just another example of so-called clicktivism—people who feel like they’re really making a difference simply by signing an online petition or sending a tweet?
Since 2011, Global Citizen says it has recorded more than 19 million “actions” from its supporters for a variety of purposes.
These actions have helped urge world leaders to announce commitments and policies worth more than $37 billion, set to impact the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
In early 2018, the group cited 390 commitments and announcements stemming from their shares, of which at least $10 billion have already been disbursed or used as funds.
The group estimates that protected capital funds have so far had a direct impact on some 649 million people worldwide.
Some of the key commitments include The Power of Nutrition, a UK-based investor-executive partnership committed to “helping children grow to their full potential,” promising to provide Rwanda with $35 million to help eliminate malnutrition in the country, after receiving more than 4,700 tweets from Global Citizens.
“With the support of the UK government, donors, national governments and Global Citizens just like you, we can make social injustice or malnutrition a footnote in history,” The Power of Nutrition ambassador Tracey Ullman told the crowd during a live concert in London in April 2018.
The group also said that after more than 5,000 actions calling on the UK to improve the nutrition of mothers and children were put in place, the government announced funding for a project, the Power of Nutrition, which will reach 5 million women and children through nutrition interventions.
In response to one of the FAQs on their website, which asked, "What makes you think we can end extreme poverty?"
Global Citizen responded: “It will be a long and arduous journey – sometimes we will fall and fail.
But, like the great civil rights and anti-apartheid movements before us, we will succeed, because together we are stronger.
Janet Jackson, the Weekend, Shawn Mendes, Cardi B, Janelle Monáe are some of those who will perform at this year’s event in New York, which will be presented by Deborra-Lee Furness and Hugh Jackman.
