Olympic swimmer Tom Daley says he grew up feeling inferior to anyone because of his sexuality — but that gave him the motivation to succeed.
The 24-year-old said he did not realize, until he arrived at secondary school, that "not everyone is like me".
Speaking on the first episode of Radio 4's Desert Island Discs, presented by Lauren Laverne, she said she had made her voice heard about gay rights to give "hope" to others.
He also said that becoming a parent made him care less about winning the Olympics.
The usual host of the long-running program, Kirsty Young, took a series of months off due to illness.
Presenting himself as an outcast on Laverne's first show, Daley said he felt "less than" anyone else as he grew up because "it was not socially acceptable that he liked both boys and girls."
He said: “Nowadays, the feeling of feeling less than, and feeling different, were the things that really gave me the strength and energy to be successful.”
He wanted to prove himself to be “something,” he said, so as not to disappoint anyone if by chance they found out about his sexuality.
The two-time Olympic bronze medalist has become a high-profile LGBT activist and has used his face at this year’s Australian Commonwealth Games to appeal to more countries to decriminalize homosexuality.
He said he made his voice heard because he felt lucky to be able to live openly without consequences and wanted to give “hope” to others.
The three-time world champion said falling in love with a man — U.S. director Dustin Lance Black, whom he met in 2013 — “took me by surprise.”
Daley married the Oscar winner, who is 20 years older than him last year, but said the age difference was never a problem.
“When you go through so many at a young age” — he went to his first Olympics when he was 14 and his father died of cancer three years later — he said it was hard to find someone of the same age who had experienced similar ups and downs.
The two became parents in June, to a child named Robert Ray Black-Daley, and Daley said his “whole perspective” has changed.
“If you asked me last year, it was all about ‘I had to win a gold medal,’” he said.
“You know, there are more important things than Olympic gold medals.
My Olympic gold medal is Robbie.”
His son bears the same name as his father Robert, who died in 2011 at the age of 40 after being diagnosed with brain cancer.
Daley said his father had not accepted the fact that he was about to die and that one of the last things he asked was if they already had tickets to London 2012 – because he wanted to be in the front row.
“I couldn’t tell him, ‘You won’t be around here so you can be in the front row, Dad,’” he said.
“I was holding his hand when he stopped breathing and until he actually stopped and died, I hadn’t realized he wasn’t invincible yet,” he said.
The following year Daley competed in the 2012 Olympics, winning the bronze.
“I just knew it was what I had dreamed of all my life – swimming in front of a home audience at the Olympic Games, there was no better feeling,” he said.
This also inspired the choice of his first song – Heather Small’s Proud – which had particular significance for him in preparing for the Olympics and still makes him goosebumps.
