The National Trust spies on the secret life of bats
New research conducted on a Scottish Highland estate aims to reveal how bats use their eyes to procure food.
It is hoped that the findings will shed light on the behaviour of the only extant flying mammals and guide future conservation activities.
The study by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland will follow bats and soprano, as well as brown earworms and Daubenton bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key locations around the property to track bat activities during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using portable detectors.
An expert’s analysis of the recorded sounds will determine the frequency of bat calls and how each species behaves.
A habitat map and a report will then be produced to create a detailed, scaled-up picture of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, nature conservation consultant for the NTS, hopes the results can reveal which areas of habitat are most important to bats and how these are used by each species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as creating meadows, and how to best maintain forests for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the UK have declined significantly over the past century.
Bats are at risk because of the construction and development work that affects the three poles and ruins the habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a threat, as can mosquito-killing paper and some chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks from domestic cats.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, because of their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to grabbing a prey.
They use a sophisticated eco-location technique to spot insects and obstacles on their trajectory.
The NTS, responsible for the care of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
Ten qualified experts regularly conduct investigations, inspect the trepoils and sometimes carry out rescues.
The organization even established Scotland's first bat-only reserve at Threave Estate in the Dumfries and Galloway region, home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
The manager of the estate, David Thompson, says that the property is the ideal territory.
“Here at Threave we have a vast area for bats,” he said.
“We have ancient buildings, many centuries-old trees and good habitat.
But there’s a lot about bats that we don’t know yet, so the work we do here and at the other properties will help us understand more about their growth needs.”
It stresses the importance of checking bats before conducting maintenance within properties as it is possible that the involuntary destruction of a single maternal trefoil could kill up to 400 females and young, possibly wiping out an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass, disturb or destroy their homes.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish head of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
“We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many of our species we don’t know how their populations are doing.”
