Here are some essential facts about Palu and Donggala on the island of Sulawesi:
Palu is the capital of the Central Sulawesi Province, located at the end of a narrow bay on the west coast of the island of Sulawesi and with a population of about 379,800 inhabitants in 2017.
When it was hit by the earthquake and tsunami, the city was celebrating its 40th anniversary.
Donggala is a regency extending along more than 300 km (180 miles) of coastline in the northwest of the island of Sulawesi.
The regency, an administrative region dependent on a province, had about 299,200 inhabitants in 2017.
Fishing and agriculture are the main sources of livelihood of the economy of the Central Sulawesi province and especially of the coastal region of Donggala.
Nickel mining is also an important activity in the province, but it is mostly concentrated in Morowali, on the opposite coast of Sulawesi.
Palu and Donggala have been hit several times by tsunamis over the past 100 years, according to Indonesia’s Disaster Mitigation Agency.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes in Donggala.
Another tsunami struck the western part of Donggala in 1996 killing nine people.
Indonesia is located in the Pacific Fire Belt and is often hit by earthquakes.
Here are some of the strongest earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years:
On December 26, 2004, a massive earthquake on the west coast of Aceh province north of Sumatra caused a tsunami that hit 14 countries killing 226,000 people along the coast of the Indian Ocean, of which more than half were from Aceh.
2005: A series of strong earthquakes struck the west coast of Sumatra between the end of March and the beginning of April.
