Red Tide Update: Concentration Is Decreasing at Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general decrease in red tide concentration in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, patchy flowering conditions, which suggest a decrease in concentration, are evident in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties.
The red tide bloom extends for about 130 miles of coastline from north of Pinellas County to south of Lee County.
The patches are about 10 miles off Hillsborough County but in fewer areas than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Last week an average concentration was reported in Pinellas County or off its coasts, a low to high concentration off Hillsborough County, from a bottom concentration to a high concentration in Manatee County, from a bottom concentration to a high concentration in Sarasota County or off its coasts, from a bottom concentration to a medium concentration in Hillsborough County.
Cases of respiratory irritation continue to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
Last week, no cases were reported in Northwest Florida.
